                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                              
	 Melbourne, March 10 (PTI): The Indian cabbie arrested for Gurshan Singh Channas death today said he had accidentally knocked the three-year-old down and driven around with the injured boy in the cars boot for three hours by mistake.          
	Gursewak Dhillon, 23, admitted dumping Gurshans body but denied deliberately injuring him, The Age reported today, as the boys parents sought a harsh punishment for the killer of their only child. Dhillon, a housemate of Gurshans parents, said the boy was hit last Thursday when he opened the door of the house in David Street, Lalor, sources said.                  
	 Lucknow : Three officials of the ashram outside whose gates 63 women and children were crushed to death in a stampede last week have been arrested though the seer who headed the institution is untraceable. Uttar Paradesh chief minister Mayavati, many of whose core constituency of Dalits perished in the stampede, herself announced the arrests of ashram trust manager Hrinmay Chatterjee, office-bearer Shiv Kumar and official Amit Kumar. They have been booked on charges of causing deaths by negligence under Section 304A of the Indian Penal Code.                   
	New Delhi (PTI): Twenty-nine elephants have been killed after being run over by trains in the country since 2007, the Lok Sabha was informed on Wednesday. Environment minister Jairam Ramesh said the matter had been taken up with the railway ministry and the state forest departments to prevent such casualties. The Centre has started an initiative, Project Elephant, for effective conservation of wild and captive elephants. It will submit its report by May.                                                                                                                                            
